        "id": 5085
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-31T14:52:34Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I see the erosion of the distinction as a step on the path towards the elimination of color filter, of which I am in favor.",
      "parentUuid": "64f176c0_60c72be7",
      "revId": "85175aba12df4252449e2812ee11bd99a0fd0479",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "6e3d4d16_1357aeb0",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-31T14:57:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m more than happy to eliminate color filters, but I don\u0027t want to break their fundamental invariant along the way.  The path to eliminating color filters can simply convert filters one by one to shaders, without adding more degrees of freedom to color filters. I don\u0027t want to have to think about two subtly different color-producing space-dependent types of effects.",
      "parentUuid": "3e70853b_654716ff",
      "revId": "85175aba12df4252449e2812ee11bd99a0fd0479",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "7dae2b71_97379c1c",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-31T15:22:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027ll say that I\u0027m not determined to land this CL - I wrote it up based on a discussion with several stakeholders. I got a little uneasy about it - I think if we\u0027re not going to do this, we do need to either:\n\n1) Make sure runtime color filters can\u0027t use position.\n2) Disallow runtime color filters entirely.\n\nI think we convinced ourselves that #2 was overly-strict, particularly if we\u0027re going to start allowing SkSL-programmable image filters, blending, etc... What\u0027s one more stage?\n\nAt the same time, we were really trying to converge on the one-true model for composition, which had evolved into \"no magic input color\" - everything comes from sampling children (and sampling a null or other sentinel valued child gets you the input (or other special) colors).\n\nUltimately - the model of sampling children to get late-bound or paint colors is very flexible (it lets you easily re-combine effects in new ways, or move them elsewhere in the Skia pipeline), but it runs into these other limitations, where some values should only be sample-able at one point (or have no spatial awareness at all). We had a similar discussion yesterday about getting the destination color for programmable blending - how do we do that if we can only (quickly) provide the pixel you\u0027re on?\n\nI don\u0027t have a good answer yet.",
      "revId": "85175aba12df4252449e2812ee11bd99a0fd0479",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e5f456fd_c6d3b9e3",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-31T15:35:59Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I do think there is a good answer here, which is to remove all color filters [1].  I just don\u0027t want to break them before we do.\n\nCan we not just force (0,0) into the local/device coordinates for runtime color filters?  You can write a space-dependent effect, and you\u0027ll just be lied to if it\u0027s used as a filter, but not when used as a composed shader of course.\n\n[1] There\u0027s a edge case where color filters are not just shader adapters today, in that paint alpha modulation happens _between_ the shader and color filter, see SkPaintPriv::RemoveColorFilter().  But it\u0027s the weird caveats like this and colorizing alpha shaders that really make me want to insist on the extreme one-true model and remove paint color too.  I want all this logic to be explicit, with some high-level could-be-external adapters to bridge over old users.",
      "parentUuid": "7dae2b71_97379c1c",
      "revId": "85175aba12df4252449e2812ee11bd99a0fd0479",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "dd39d212_e37a6cee",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-31T15:56:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I guess the tricky part comes when an effect calls sample(kid, xy), right?\n\nsample(kid) with no explicit xy should work just fine for any effect, and would be the main way effects can be used as color filters.\n\nI\u0027d think if we want to guarantee an effect used as color filter sees only its single input, in addition to providing (0,0) local and device coordinates, and perhaps too obvious to say only allowing one child, we\u0027d also need to make sample(kid, xy) return sample(kid).  It\u0027s not enough to not know where you are... you also have to allow access to exactly that one color to be a color filter.  If an effect calls sample(kid) and then later sample(kid,xy) with xy depending on the result of the first sample(kid) call, that filter\u0027s not space-invariant.\n\nI don\u0027t have a strong opinion on whether we should analyze the effect for non-color-filter properties and return null on creation, or allow these effects to make color filters while disabling features that could let them be spatially-sensitive.  My main point is that if we want to make a runtime effect act as a color filter, let\u0027s restrict the effect to the constraints of a color filter, not change the rules of color filters to accommodate our shared implementation with runtime shaders.\n\nThis will come up with blend modes too... today we allow our blend modes to depend on two varying pixels only, and when those two pixels (or properties of them) are known we can confidently apply the blend mode or strength reduce the math.  If we let a blend mode depend on arbitrary inputs, we\u0027ll lose that constraint.",
      "parentUuid": "e5f456fd_c6d3b9e3",
      "revId": "85175aba12df4252449e2812ee11bd99a0fd0479",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
